summary: but are they gay harold
title: but are they gay harold
body:
Here, have a fun “welcome-to-the-shipping-side-of-fandom” collection of cites. Feel free to add.

Neil Gaiman: it’s “not unreasonabl[e]” to ship Crowley with Aziraphale, and he can “just about get [his] head around the concept,” even if he’d rather not read any of the slash. After all, there are things you can “never unsee.”

David Tennant: Crowley “absolutely loves” Aziraphale although hates that he loves him, “it’s really annoying for him.” He’s called the relationship “more of a marriage” than a friendship.

Michael Sheen: wanted to play Aziraphale as “sort of in love” with Crowley, or alternately, his character “just loves” Crowley (he recalls trying not to just “gaze longingly” at him all the time). Elsewhere he has called the show “a love story for the 21st century.”

the text: fades out with the nightingale. Oh, and they moved in together (this comment, elaborated on at a bookreading/signing event).

Is it explicitly canon? No, says Gaiman. Well, it’s never explicit, says Sheen, but there is a kind of “interesting love story.”

summary: FanFic Teaser in which Hell is effectively ineffective.
title: FanFic Teaser in which Hell is effectively ineffective.
body:
I started writing that GO fanfic. Have a teaser:

“However,” said Lucifer after a dreadful pause that was just long enough to not let Hastur relish in his victory as much as he’d liked to. “There will be a new assignment for you.”

Hastur nodded curtly, albeit a little taken aback. And caught the slip of paper that appeared in midair. Belphegor looked at Crowley.

“As for you. From here on you’ll be accompanied by a…” she casted an amused look at Hastur, “Uh… chaperone.”

Both, Crowley and Hastur stiffened.

“What?” they blurted out in unison, followed by an equally synchronized glower at the other.

“It’s been decided,” Asmodeus added, smiling at the two lower demons with the kind and friendly expression of a TV preacher. “Duke Hastur, just let it be said you are not to harm your ward. Are there any complains you would like to make?”

Plenty, Crowley thought bitterly, looking at Hastur, who, by the looks of it, not only shared his sentiments, but was inwardly blessing profoundly.

“None,” said Hastur then, standing stiff as a plank.

“You may go then. Your assignment awaits.”

—

Crowley couldn’t get out of the Council Hall quickly enough. Blessed Heaven he should have expected this.

Especially after Aziraphale mentioned he’d be getting a supervisor.

This wasn’t fair.

Oh, who was he kidding? This was Hell, he had stopped an Apocalypse AND killed a higher ranking demon. Under these circumstances whatever he had coming here could be counted as ’fair’.

He straightened his posture and looked back at Hastur, who was leaning against the wall, almost melting into the shadows.

“Guess we’re living together then,” said Crowley. In a tone as if he was apologizing for his existence.

Hastur looked up from the note he’d been studying, and quirked a brow. “Think again.”

Crowley whistled through his teeth. “You defying orders? I’ll be blessed.”

Hastur grinned, “Careful what you wish for.” He handed him the note.

It was an address.

Crowley was about to say something about Hastur knowing his old slash new apartment, when the address wormed its way into his brain.

He paled.

“I’m not your chaperone, Crowley,” said Hastur, with bitter amusement. “Am to keep an eye on that angel of yours.”

summary: angst, yes please
title: angst, yes please
body:
What am I doing to myself? (from my wip) under the cut:

“Make love…” Aziraphale sneered. “You don’t know what that is.”

Crowley’s frown grew deeper, but he didn’t interrupt. He continued to glare at his angel–

No…this angel. This wasn’t Aziraphale. Something new was stirring in him, something Crowley had never seen in him before, and it made his fists clench and his stomach churn.

Hatred. That’s what it was. Hatred toward him. Crowley didn’t think angels were capable, but he felt it in Aziraphale at that moment, and wanted to shrink.

“You may think you know,” the angel continued, staring back at him, his eyes becoming wet. “You may know how to say it, how to insert it into a sentence to have what you want, but you’ll never understand it.”

Aziraphale paused to sniff back his tears. He didn’t like feeling this way toward his constant companion, but he felt deceived.

“You don’t feel love, Crowley,” he muttered, throwing on his dressing gown. He snapped the sash into a disheveled knot and stepped closer. “Because it’s of no use to you.”

“You may think you know,” the angel continued, staring back at him, his eyes becoming wet. “You may know how to say it, how to insert it into a sentence to have what you want, but you’ll never understand it.”

Aziraphale paused to sniff back his tears. He didn’t like feeling this way toward his constant companion, but he felt deceived.

“You don’t feel love, Crowley,” he muttered, throwing on his dressing gown. He snapped the sash into a disheveled knot and stepped closer. “Because it’s of no use to you.”

summary: REALLY
body:
So you know that idiot thing we do, where a server says “enjoy your meal,” or the ticket agent at the theater says “enjoy the show”, and we say “you too.”

I had a thought.

I really,

really

REALLY

want the ending scene of Good Omens to be Aziraphale and Crowley on the phone, and the final shot is Aziraphale, smiling in his new bookshop, saying goodbye and starting to hang up. And then from the other end, in that same “you too” tone, Crowley just says, “Ta, love you.”

And then Aziraphale says “wait, what??” And then CLICK. Phone hangs up, screen goes black, ROLL CREDITS.jpg

summary: The sun doesn't set on the shoreline
title: The sun doesn't set on the shoreline
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2Jmt9Vf

by VinWrit

They say that the sun never sets on Eden House.
They also say that Eden House is haunted. Nobody in the nearby villages ever visited the old manor, and its strange occupant. They said that he was mad. Mad Mister Fell, they called him. Poor old Mister Fell.

They said that sirens live in the deep, wild oceans; at the bottom of the Mariana Trench: and that selkies live in the north, near Ireland and Finland and in parts of Alaska.

On all counts, they were largely wrong.
